Returns the OS error that this error represents (if any).

If this [`Error`](struct.Error.html "struct std::io::Error") was constructed via [`last_os_error`](about:blank/struct.Error.html#method.last_os_error "associated function std::io::Error::last_os_error") or [`from_raw_os_error`](about:blank/struct.Error.html#method.from_raw_os_error "associated function std::io::Error::from_raw_os_error"), then this function will return [`Some`](about:blank/option/enum.Option.html#variant.Some "variant std::option::Option::Some"), otherwise it will return [`None`](about:blank/option/enum.Option.html#variant.None "variant std::option::Option::None").

##### [Â§](#examples-4)Examples

```
use std::io::{Error, ErrorKind};

fn print_os_error(err: &Error) {
    if let Some(raw_os_err) = err.raw_os_error() {
        println!("raw OS error: {raw_os_err:?}");
    } else {
        println!("Not an OS error");
    }
